title: Parametric Threaded Ogive Rocket Nose Cone

description.text: Fully parametric ogive nose cone with a screw-on base. This allows the nosecone to be entirely printed, and used as a small payload bay. The ogive shape is created by revolving a circular arc, combined with a spherical tip. Uses syvwlch's thread library. More parametric model rocket parts to come. Default size is for some extra thin-walled 1.63"/41.5mm diameter cardboard body tube I have. Includes integrated reinforcement bar and mounting holes for tying a shock cord to the base. Now available at Github: https://github.com/bld/Parametric-Threaded-Ogive-Rocket-Nose-Cone

• Download syvwlch's Screw Library: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8793
  • Measure body tube inner & outer diameters and enter
  • Select other parameters
  • Render & export STL for "fitcheck" part
  • Print fitcheck.stl and check fit in body tube. It shouldn't be too tight or too loose. You want it to come loose easily with the ejection charge, but not rattle around.
  • Adjust & reprint if necessary.
  • Print nosecone and base once the fitcheck part works to your liking.
  • Thread shock cord through holes in base and tie.
  • Screw cone onto base.
    • I printed this on my Makergear Mosaic with the following Slic3r settings:
  • No support material
  • 0.25 mm layer thickness
  • 3 solid layers, 2 perimeters
  • 0.1 fill density with rectilinear fill
    • Notes:
  • The threads tend to curl up a little while printing at 0.25 mm, but the base and cone do so equally so the threaded together without trouble.
  • Due to some slack in the threads, the base can end up slightly off-center when tightened. Unscrew and rescrew pressing away from the side that's short.
  • Mine came out a little heavy, so for smaller, lighter rockets, check the balance to make sure it isn't too nose heavy: http://www.wikihow.com/Calculate-Stability-of-a-Model-Rocket

title: Slew Bearing - Customizable
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a complete reimplementation in OpenSCAD of the slew bearing created by Christoph Laimer. He implemented it in Fusion360 and made a nice Youtube video on how to design such a thing and testing it, highly recommended!

The main features of this over the one by Christoph Laimer are:

  • customizable in Customizer
  • integrated threads, so no need for additional screws
  • tension adjustable (unscrew a bit to reduce tension)

I highly recommend printing the rollers in vase mode to get best possible surface quality. If your slicer allows, add some bottom and top layers to make the rollers stiffer.
The outer ring can be printed in one part, but two parts may provide better surface quality because otherwise there is a 45 degrees overhang.

The bearing height will determine your roller diameter and height, i recommend using a height of 8mm or more, otherwise it might be challanging to print and tolerances must be small.
I successfully printed bearings from 70x25mm diameter down to 13x2.5mm.
Without screwable outer ring 11mm should be possible. Rollers cant be printed that small, but you can use small chunks of 1.75mm filament as rollers.

Hints:

  • Number of rollers are not (yet) automatically optimized. You should design it with minimal distance between rollers and number of rollers must be even! Easiest to adjust by changing height of bearing
  • This does not feature the very cool kegel style rollers as designed by Christopf Laimer

description.text:
Meka Dragon from King of Tokyo. Designed to replace the cardboard cutout that comes with the game. Some assembly required.

If you're feeling adventurous, you can try to print the full model as one piece. Let me know how it goes. Otherwise, there are two sets of files available: FULL and FLAT. First, the COMMON files are needed in any case. Then, you can either print the FLAT files, in which tricky parts are split in half with the flat side facing the print platform. These will be easier to print, but will require more assembly later. The FULL pieces will be more difficult to print neatly with a filament printer due to overhangs, but will require less assembly after printing.

The head should be printed with support. It is aligned the way it is to keep the support material out of the teeth, from where it would be a pain to remove.

Some notes about printing the FULL parts:

  • The body should be printable without supports, but the segment seams may sag a bit. Use supports if you're not sure about printing overhangs
  • All the limbs and the tail should be printed with supports, too. They're aligned to ensure the connector studs print ok.

You can find the rest of the King of Tokyo monsters in this collection. There is also a blog post with more information about the models.

Assembly

The parts need to be glued together. If you printed the FLAT parts, start by gluing the two halves of each part together first. Here I used plenty of ABS slurry to make sure any gap between the halves gets filled. Any excess slurry can be cut or filed off once the its is set.

Test fit each part before applying glue; The parts may need minor filing or sanding to fit.

This is my interpetation of the Fergus Falls Regional Treatment Center. It is a dying part of our history and is in danger of being torn down. From the pictures to the actual files I have added many windows and other features to make it more accurate. (This description is borrowed from Kirkbridebuildings.com) In the late nineteenth-century, overcrowding at Minnesota's two Kirkbride asylums in Rochester and St. Peter led to the creation of a third in Fergus Falls. Construction began in 1888 and was finished with completion of the central administration structure in 1906. Warren Dunnel of Minneapolis, Minnesota was the architect. While most Kirkbrides have wings divided by sections joining at right angles, the sections here join at much wider angles. The resulting rough curve of the building's footprint is echoed in arched windows and the rounded turrets and connecting hallways. This gives the building a graceful and grand appearance which is somewhat offset by the rectangular central tower of the administration section. Much of the interior has been renovated extensively and is very modern. Original decorative elements still remain however, such as the ornate staircase in the center part of the Kirkbride, and the pervasive mosaic tiled floors. There are also some areas that have changed little since the early twentieth-century â€” a few wards in the North-East wing, and some staff living quarters in the administration area â€” but even these disused sections appear to be in solid condition. Although still partly in use, the hospital has been declared surplus property by the state of Minnesota. The patient population has shrunk significantly and will soon be non-existant within the Kirkbride. The buildings and grounds are available for development in the near future and the city of Fergus Falls and the state of Minnesota are offering several incentives to anybody deciding to develop the property. For information on preservation and/or re-development please see Fergus Falls Regional Treatment Center at FergusPhotos.com. *Update - As of 2009 the FFRTC has been compleatly abandoned and is no longer being used. MBot's recent inexpensive single extruder 3D printer kit is a hoot but it lacks an easy way to guide the filament from the rear spool hanger up to the extruder. After considering an up-and-over guide bar or full on overhead hanger I settled on the traditional 6mm x 4mm guide tube.

The rear panel is just a simple tube and two brackets. Print two copies of the rear bracket; it flips over to make the opposite end.

The extruder side fits in the gap in the sheet metal umbilical holder. Push in the slotted side and the other end should snap into place. The flexibility of ABS helps here but PLA would probably work with care (or file down the end of the tongue just a little).

STP versions are included in addition to the printable STLs to support customization. I hate trying to modify STLs; they never turn out well. The extruder side bracket could probably be made beefier.

For the tubing I'm using a length of 6 x 4 mm PTFE. 1/4 inch poly tubing would probably work if the brackets are reamed slightly with a 1/4" drill.

Update: See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2580309 for a different take on the rear holder.

The model is based on the Temple of Portunus, also known as the Temple of Fortuna Virilis, which stands near the Tiber in Rome (see photograph). The temple dates from the first century B.C. but was converted to a Christian church in the 9th century, by enclosing the ancient structure in brickwork. In the 1920s, the additions were all stripped away, to reveal the original structure, and a great deal of conservation work has been carried out more recently.

THE MODEL is printed in several parts, designed to slot neatly into each other for correct positioning:
The PODIUM (or base) is in two parts, the front part with steps also includes the shafts of the portico pillars (with entasis.)
The CELLA (the central enclosed structure) is printed in two parts including the 'engaged' half-columns.
The ENTABLATURE (the part with the frieze between the tops of the pillars and the roof) is again printed in two parts, the front part includes the Ionic capitals for the portico columns.
The ROOF is also in two parts, and there are four 'connectors' (printed separately,) designed position the roof pieces correctly on the entablature.
The parts can be fixed together permanently with a few dabs of super-glue applied during assembly.
The overall size of the assembled model is 19.6cm. x 9.6cm. x 12.5cm. high.

Print all parts in the orientation shown.
The model was printed on my Fifth Generation Makerbot at the default settings.

Podium front (+ columns) - 5hr. 36min.

  • 6 x LEDMatrix module with MAX7219 driver
  • supplied directly from USB port with USB plug
  • all data are synchronized every 7-8 minutes
  • time and date are taken from google.com
  • weather informations are grabbed from openweather.org JSON api
  • in the future also other news and infos grabbing can be possible
  • no hardware RTC clock is necessary
  • internal temperature, humidity sensor (options - DS18B20, DHT22, DHT12)
  • ESP8266 setup and control as a Wi-Fi Web Server (WiFiManager, OTA, mDNS)
  • receives a message input from a User Input page, then displays the message on a scrolling LED matrix display.

Parts List:

  • 6 x MAX7219 8 x 8 LED Matrix module
  • 1 x WeMos D1 mini
  • 1 x Interface shield

Additional Parts:

  • N x DS18B20 temperature sensor
  • 1 x DHT22 temperature and humidity sensor
  • 1 x DHT12 temperature and humidity sensor
  • N x WS2812B RGB LED

title: Infinitely Inside out turnable Magic Cube

description.text: Flip this thing inside out many many times and become mesmerized by the ever changing features of the cube. If you flip this thing completely inside out, it will actually not be a cube anymore but a spiky geometric shape!

ve always wanted to build this and hopefully I can if I win this MakerBot. I initially got the idea with those little trade show toys you get that allows you to 'flip' the cube inside out. They morph and can eventually show a total of 12 sides (6 outside and 6 stored inside). They are called magic cubes because they suddenly can make a picture seem like it appears out of nowhere. So the twist is rather than put boring pictures on the 6 faces of the block, I am to store geometric shapes inside the hidden surfaces. You can think of it as 3 pyramids stuck together to form a sub cube part. Then 8 of those sub cube parts are put together to form the final product. Here you can see the inside of the cube where I have joined all the side appropriately. The actual file for one eighth the part is shown here:

description.text:
Hi,

This is a battery pack for those cheap drills that were produced around 2003 - 2015. Einhell, Defort, Ferm, Challenge, Amtech, ProUser, Speedway, Workzone, Power-G, Boston, Draper, XU1, Trades Pro and Top Craft (maybe Mastercraft) made (or relabeled) them. You can find pictures of those drills on the page of the original design.

This is a rework of my first cheap drill battery.

After printing and testing my first battery, I found it was a bit heavy and the parallel setup was too much for my drills. It can run forever without needing a recharge. I decided more voltage (4.2 x 5 = ~20)) from five 18650 cells and no cells in parallel would be better.

So this new thing is just that. Room for 5 cells and the same fitting on top. It uses the space more efficiently, is a lot smaller and provides more angry pixies to the drill.

I noticed my design will support 6 cells as well. (that was not intentional). I already tried it and my drills seem to be ok with 6 cells, but still, better safe than sorry. 25,2V is a lot of juice for chintzy drills like these.

Have fun.

Yes

50%

Notes:

My software reports a print time of 3h35m. I do print with optimized settings for speed and strength. Quality is less of an issue with this sort of thing.

Instructions

This pack is a bit different from the previous one. You will have to solder the 18650 in series. My previous pack was made with contacts and stuff, mainly because I didn't want to solder my good 18650's without knowing if it would actually work. Now, a year later, I know it works very well, so soldering up a pack isn't a concern any more.

Make sure you use 18650 cells that have enough power. They should be able to deliver the amps your drill needs without overheating.

Solder five 18650 up in series. Use at least 16 Amp gauge wire. Tape the cells or glue them, do whatever you want to keep them together and put them in the thing. Run the wires up to the top, make some contacts and attach your wires.

Use superglue to get the lid to stay on the pack.

Note that the clicky mechanism I included in the previous version is gone. I removed them from the design and I also removed the clips from my drills. They just don't provide a secure connection of the battery. I use an industrial rubber band to keep the battery on the drill. Works way better.

Custom choocher done.

Additional information

To charge these batteries I use my adjustable power supply. I disassembled the old charger, threw it's guts out and ran wires to the contacts. I made wires that can plug in to my power supply.

Make sure to check your charging voltages. Li-Ion batteries are dangerous!

Do not, i repeat, do not charge in a Ni-Cd charger. The cells will overheat, explode or even burn your house down.

You have been warned.

Specifications

5 x LG 2400Mah = 18,5V - 2,4Ah (charge at 21V - 500Mah)
5 x Samsung ICR18650 28A = 18,5V - 2,8Ah (higher charge voltage 4,3V/cell so 21,5V - 500Mah)

6 x LG 2400Mah = 22,2V - 2,4Ah (charge at 25,2V - 500Mah)

Don't use the cheap chineseum cells. They will give you a bad time. One exception. Efest 3000Mah. Those actually work.

Always check datasheets for allowed discharge rate. You should at the very least be able to discharge them at 5A. Otherwise you are creating a custom flame thrower.

Why?

Better performance.
Li-Ion cells don't lose their charge as fast as Ni-Cd or Ni-Mh
Recycling / Upcycling
New drills / battery packs are expensive
I have a lot of these drills.
I have a lot of 18650 cells available (from old notebooks / power tools / bikes)

description.text:
It's a very small and handy power supply: 30x18x14 mm. USB to 3.3V and 5V so it works with powerbanks and mobile chargers. Very useful for DIY electronics projects.

Well, it could also be something completely different (and much bigger). It's really a customizable enclosure. It's based on paul0's Ultimate PSU Profile Box.

Tweakable parameters (also see attached drawing):

  • Length, width and thickness of board
  • clearance above and below PCB
  • thickness of the box itself
  • depth of the groove, where the board sits.
  • inclusion/exclusion of the following features: USB connector, cable pass-through, fan grill, ventilation/outtakes
  • the position (height) of the USB connector and the diameter of the pass-through and the fan can be customized.

The initial parameter settings (when you click Open in Customizer) yield the same result as the attached STL files, namely the power supply in the photos. It would be fun to see your makes and customized design. Please, post photos!

Electronics

I used the following parts

  • A micro-USB breakout board, which I glued :-) to a piece of breadboard
  • An MCP1700-3302E Voltage Regulator. Yeah, that's the little black fly dirt. 2x1 mm or something like that.
  • Two 1 uF ceramic capacitors (the blue blobs)
  • Black, red and orange wires with female headers in one end (used to have headers in both ends). As in an ATX PSU, black is ground, red is +5V and orange is 3V.

The circuit is really simple. See Microchip MCP1700. Capacitors on both input and output.

I picked the MCP1700 because it's so small. Drawback is that it only delivers 250 mA. If you don't mind a slightly bigger box, you can go for a regulator with more oomph.

Once you know the dimensions of your board and the required clearance, you can start customizing the enclosure.

Pull the wires into the pass-through before soldering them to the board. The headers are too big for the pass-through, so you can't reverse the order of those steps.

Tools for blanking out Suction Cup Stefans/Slugs (SCS) foam darts more quickly.

Read more about SCS's here:
http://nerfhaven.com/forums/topic/27314-scs-suction-cup-slug/

SCS-cutter-proto3-1.STL and SCS-cutter-proto3-2.STL assemble together to create an enclosed housing. Remove the supports on the retention tabs, and they should snap in place with a bit of aligning. This file has been tested once and is in its 3rd iteration.

SCS-gluing-pods.STL is for assisting the gluing process, similar to Kane's templates for letting Silidomes cure. This file has not yet been tested.

Pros:

  • Faster and more efficient dart head snipping and foam blank cutting.
  • More consistent blanking lengths.
  • Pods should enable faster gluing application techniques.

Cons:

  • Snipping suction cups out is still annoying and has to be done a certain way to achieve a flat dart head, but can be done a few at a time now.
  • Foam blank requires a very sharp blade to cut cleanly, but even then your milage may vary depending on technique.
  • Unable to rotate the foam easily while snipping or cutting, resulting in the disadvantages above.

These items are still in fairly early development phases, but the cutting jig has been working so far. If needed, it should be relatively easy to modify the design for other varieties of cutdown darts. This jig is designed for 1.5" foam lengths, and some may prefer 1.25".

Other notes:

  • Definitely make sure the bed is leveled, flat, and clean.
  • Definitely print with supports on the retention tabs, unless you're certain of your printer's bridging capabilities.

title: CR-10 Enclosure clips for Home Depot plexiglass

description.text:
Clips to hold plexiglass in place as part of my CR-10 3D printer enclosure. These clips are designed to work with 0.093 inch thick plexiglass sold at Home Depot. (https://www.homedepot.com/p/OPTIX-20-in-x-32-in-x-093-in-Acrylic-Sheet-MC-17/202038049)

There are two different clips. one bottom clip that is flat (for bottom) so that the plexiglass can rest on flat. The other clip is rotatable (for side and top) so that you can easily remove the plexiglass by rotating the clips out of the way.

The enclosure frame is built using solid oak hardwood. (It's actually 1 1/4 inch red oak stair baluster from Home Depot. https://www.homedepot.com/p/Stair-Parts-41-in-x-1-1-4-in-Unfinished-Red-Oak-Square-Baluster-5060R-041-HD00L/202088535)

The finish is two coats of Minwax satin Polyurethane.
https://www.homedepot.com/p/Minwax-1-qt-Clear-Satin-Fast-Drying-Polyurethane-Interior-Wood-Protective-Finish-63010/100201939

I design the frame so that I can lift the entire frame away from the bottom. I got the idea from this build https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2012384.

The hinges are lift-off hinges so that I can easily remove the entire door by lifting the plexiglass. (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B017FX1H5Q)

The door handle is from this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1228617. The door is held in place closed by magnet. The door stop with magnet holder is here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2186895.

The most tricky part of building this enclosure is cutting the plexiglass as it's relatively thin at 0.093 and flexes when cutting. It's very easy to chip the last few centimeters even using a special plexiglass jigsaw blade. I ended up having to build a special jig (basically sandwich the plexiglass between two thin pieces of plywood) to cut the plexiglass.

description.text:
A cable protector for cable laid on the floor.

This was designed for flat HDMI and VGA cables laid between the gaming computer and a projector. The segments (links) allow the protector to follow a curved path. A low profile, from customizability to just fit the cables, gives additional safety. Use tape to hold the cable in place. Double sided carpet tape can be used on the floor-side to hold the protector to the floor.

Most flat cables will take a 3 mm height on a hardwood floor. The customizer defaults are for a "standard" round cable core of 13 mm (0.5"). Carpeted floor will stress the cable and protector more due to the substrate flex. You can minimize breakage of the bridge and cable by using a greater attack angle, looser fit, and a narrower, thicker bridge.

For round cables,
Attack angle = 30
Channel height = 13
Channel width = 13
Wall = 2 // equivalent to bridge thickness

For flat cables,
Attack angle = 12
Channel height = 3
Channel width = 20
Wall = 2 // equivalent to bridge thickness

The protector is supplied in three versions. A customizer selector, CM_link.scad, shows proper assembly in the "both" setting. The other two settings allow parts to be made singly for small bed printers. Making channels wider than the cable allows for the protector to curve.

An attack angle of <=12 degrees is recommended for those with disabilities (ADA compliant). This recommendation is relaxed for height changes of less than 12 mm outdoors. There is no specific recommendation for indoor uses. Many commercial cable protectors use attack angles of >20 degrees to achieve heights of 16 mm or more.

Customizer notes:
Some settings break the model. Wide channel widths, high channel heights and low attack angles are not compatible. No bound checking is implemented.

You will notice that on low attack angles the customizer displays a very tiny object. The underlying, masked out cylinder is quite large. The printed size may also be quite large. Like an iceberg, you only get to see the upper 10%!

title: Bicycle spoke nipple insertion tool
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I enjoy building bike wheels, and I enjoy nice tools. I also enjoy 3D printing and making nice tools with the 3D printer. This is one of those cases. In the photo on the top is a $20 spoke nipple insertion tool, (I'm not affiliated with BHS but am a very happy customer) it's a really nice piece of steel with a taper on the pointy end that creates a friction fit when inserted in the top of a spoke nipple, which allows you to pass the spoke nipple through the rim and thread it onto the spoke. I've used other spokes in the past, but you have to take time to thread the spoke nipple onto the spare spoke, and then thread it off, and that takes time. Using the tapered end and the friction fit is much, much faster.

I had an idea of how I could create my own version - yes, even though I already bought the fancy one - that anyone could 3D print. I searched until I found a screwdriver handle that I liked - see the sources for a fantastic little screwdriver handle, then cleaned it up, gutted it, cut off the threads and scaled it down. I put a hole in the end, and sized this to around 2mm. Into this hole, I inserted a piece of wire clothes hanger, which measures 2.3mm and is therefore large enough to get the friction fit once the end is tapered.

To make your own, find a wire clothes hanger - or any wire that's around 2.3mm in diameter. Cut it to length, and then file or grind a taper on the end. This may take some doing, and I suggest having a spare spoke nipple on hand to test the friction fit. Once you've done that, put the wire in a vice with the taper pointing down, and lightly hammer the wire into the handle. Voila! Bicycle spoke nipple inserter.

To make getting at the spoke nipples from the top as easy as possible, be sure to check out my spoke nipple shuffler - it quickly organizes spoke nipples so they're heads up, making it really quick and easy to grab one as needed.

Happy wheelbuilding!

Update: I built a wheel using this instead of my purchased tool for the same purpose, and have to say that it worked quite well. The only issue I have is the taper on the end of the wire is a bit too gradual - it holds the nipple quite well but the tip continues and it winds up hitting the spoke. This isn't a huge problem, and could be addressed by shortening the pointed end of the tip.

description.text:
This is a remix of this great Mobius Mini camera mount by UltiBots https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2451154.

Changes:

  • Reduced the tilt to 10 degrees.
  • Added cutout for SD Card slot so that you can remove the SD card.
  • Cut out a small section of bottom mount to make it easier to get a grip and remove Mobius Mini from the mount.

I used SainSmart TPU on a CR-10 with an upgraded metal extruder drive feed for flexible filament. Nozzle temp 220C and bed temp 70C at 15mm/s 1st layer and 30mm/s rest. No fan. I used 10mm retraction at 100mm/s and also turned on coasting to avoid blobs and stringing.

title: CP2102 TTL to USB Programmer Case
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After printing out https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1557552, I noticed that my CP2102 programmer from the same source wouldn't quite fit due to manufacturing differences. Also, I had no M2 screws lying around.

So I set about creating my own from scratch in OpenSCAD. One that would allow for these manufacturing differences/defects, but also allow a snug, snap-fit design with nice viewing windows for pin labels on the bottom and LEDs on the top.

38 versions later, and here it is. Instead of screws, this design uses built-in pins in M3 sized holes. The pins are slightly smaller in diameter than the holes to allow for a decent fit.

Update: I've uploaded a version 39 which may be useful if you're having a loose fit for your CP2102 programmer. The files ending in v39 have smaller pin tolerances for the upper and a small extra plate at the front of the bottom piece to level it out if the pins on the bottom of the board in the rear are longer than the ones in the front.

title: H Of Truce Board Game
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
H Of Truce (By Christian Heckmann) is a short, abstract game of tactical tile movement for two players. The object of the game is to capture the enemy's commander with one of your own soldiers.
Both players control six soldier pieces who move across an ever changing playing field and try to reach the enemies immobile commander piece via an "action inflation"-mechanic: Both players alternate turns, always taking one action more than their opponent had beforehand, until the game ends or one of the players chooses to reset the action point track back to one action, if he spots a way for his opponent to win with the number of actions he would get. This leads to short, dynamic games with almost no luck, but a lot of clever moves and surprises.
